ce:section.ce:para:
For ensuring the in vitro biosafety during anti-cancer therapy, the biocompatibility of GdOF:Yb3+/Er3+@(GNDs@BSA)–DOX–FA particles (hereinafter abbreviated to GGBDFs) with varied volume of GNDs solution were assayed by standard MTT method. No matter how the concentration of GGBDFs changed, practically every L929 fibroblast cells were survived, and no obvious cytotoxicity was shown after 24 h incubation, indicating the good biocompatibility of GGBDFs (Fig. S4a). In order to guarantee the biocompatibility of the nanohybrids since the GGBDFs might be decomposed by cell sap and photothermal induction, UCNPs and GNDs@BSA were also examined as the same process. As Fig. Sb,c displayed, the cell viability of UCNPs and GNDs@BSA in the whole range were over 95%, which also presents the ideal in vitro biocompatibility. Afterwards, the cellular uptake behavior of GGBDFs was evaluated on HeLa cancer cells (Fig. 3
                        ). With the uptake time gradually increased from 0.5 h to 3 h, the intensity of fluorescence obtained from confocal laser scanning microscopy (CLSM) images apparently became much stronger, suggesting that more and more fluorescence labeling entered the cancer cells. Because the uptake of DAPI and DOX has a certain time difference, fluorescence color achieved form overlay images is converted from violet to pink, interpreting that GGBDFs can be aggregated in HeLa cancer cells via cell membrane crossing. Further quantitative examination of GGBDFs uptake was performed on inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (ICP-MS). As Fig. S5 shown, a larger amount of Au was measured in the cells with the prolongation of uptake time, confirming the good compatibility and cell uptake behavior of GGBDFs. Based on the excellent fluorescence capacity and cytocompatibility of GGBDFs, in vitro UCL imaging was performed on HeLa cells. After 1 h incubation and 980 nm NIR excitation, the fluorescence emission of the sample without GNDs is much stronger and redder than that of 3 mL GNDs added, which not only meets with the tendency of fluorescence spectra but also indirectly confirms the biocompatibility of GGBDFs (Fig. 4
                        a).
